@node "Description" "Description"

                                @{fg shine}DESCRIPTION@{fg text}

    @{b}PGP5GUI@{ub} provides an MUI Graphic User Interface to ease the use of PGP 5
    on the AMIGA platform.  Specifically, it is a collection of buttons and
    gadgets you can manipulate to do almost all functions related to PGP 5.

    @{b}PGP5GUI@{ub} can be used with any CPU.

    @{b}PGP5GUI@{ub} is currently @{fg shine}FREEWARE@{fg text}.
@endnode

@node "Installing" "Installing"

                                @{fg shine}INSTALLING@{fg text}

    1.  You can put @{b}PGP5GUI@{ub} anywhere you like.

        The important thing to remember is that @{" PGPE " link "PGP:PGP5.guide/PGPE" 0}, @{" PGPS " link "PGP:PGP5.guide/PGPS" 0}, @{" PGPV " link "PGP:PGP5.guide/PGPV" 0} and
         PGPK  must be accessible to @{b}PGP5GUI@{ub}" link "PGP:PGP5.guide/PGPK" 0} must be accessible to PGP5GUI.

        The best place to have PGPE, PGPS, PGPV and PGPK, is in your "@{fg shine}C:@{fg text}"
        drawer...  Most programs look for other programs in the "C:" drawer
        so it's probably the best place for @{b}PGP5GUI@{ub} too.


    2.  You should also put this AmigaGuide file (you are reading) in your
        assigned "@{fg shine}PGP:@{fg text}" directory.  @{b}PGP5GUI@{ub} has links to this AmigaGuide
        document and uses it to display 'Help' information about a page,
        button, or gadget.

        @{b}PGP5GUI@{ub} will look for this AmigaGuide file if you press the [Help]
        key on any of the 'hotspots'.

        These 'hotspots are:
            a) On a button or gadget for help about the button or gadget.
            b) Just outside of a button or gadget for help about a page.


    3.  If you have it, you should also put @{fg shine}PGP5.guide@{fg text} into your assigned
        "PGP:" directory.  The PGP5.guide is available from my web-site at:

            @{fg shine}http://www.amitar.com.au/~stef/DownloadsPGP5.html@{fg text}

        look for the archive @{fg shine}pgp5guides.lha@{fg text} on that page.

        The PGP5GUI.guide (you are reading) has links to PGP5.guide.

        If you have correctly installed PGP5.guide, then if you

           @{" click this button " link "PGP:PGP5.guide/main" 0}

        the next document you see should be the main page of PGP5.guide.
@endnode

@node "Usage" "Usage"

                                   @{fg shine}USAGE@{fg text}

    From Workbench: Double-click the icon.
    From Shell/CLI: PGP5GUI

    See @{" Notes " link "Notes" 0} for more information about this program.

    You MUST have @{fg shine}Magic User Interface V3.8@{fg text} installed and operational on
    your system before attempting to use @{b}PGP5GUI@{ub}.

    When @{b}PGP5GUI@{ub} starts, you will be presented with a GUI that has four
    "Pages" on it.  These "pages" are:

                     @{" Encrypt - For Encrypting a file " link "Encrypt_Group" 0}

                     @{" Decrypt - For Decrypting a file " link "Decrypt_Group" 0}

                     @{"    Sign - For Signing a file    " link "Sign_Group" 0}

                     @{"    Keys - PGP Key management    " link "Keys_Group" 0}
@endnode

@node "Notes" "Notes"

                                   @{fg shine}NOTES@{fg text}

    When a requester pops up asking you for a key, or keys to select,
    pressing [Ok] will begin the operation on the SELECTED key(s) in most
    cases.  If no keys are selected, then it is assumed that you wish to
    abort the operation.

    There is one exception to the above mentioned rule - @{" Check Key(s) " link "ED_KEYCHECK" 0}
    will check ALL keys if [Ok] is selected.

    Pressing [Cancel] or the [Close Window] gadget will abort the operation
    before you begin and take you back to the main GUI window.

    The default "UserID" used for Encrypting/Signing/Key operations is the
    one PGP 5 considers the default UserID.  This is the one you have
    specified in the @{" MyName= " link "PGP:PGP5.guide/PGP-CFG" 83} line of @{" pgp.cfg " link "PGP:PGP5.guide/PGP-CFG" 0}.  If no key is specified
    as the default, then PGP 5 will use the first usable key found on your
    secret keyring.

    When you exit @{b}PGP5GUI@{ub}, all of the 'cycle' gadgets will have their
    settings saved to:

        @{b}ENVARC:mui/PGP5GUI.1.cfg@{ub}

    Also, the 'AmigaPGP5 Output Window...' and the ASL File Requesters will
    have their positions and dimensions saved to a file called:

        @{b}ENVARC:PGP5GUI.wcfg@{ub}

    The ASL FIle Requesters will also have the last used file and path names
    saved to the above file too.

    The next time you run @{b}PGP5GUI@{ub}, these settings will be reloaded and used.
    See @{" BUGS " link "Bugs" 0} for a problem I found with the ASL File Requester.

    If you have any ideas, suggestions, or want something changed/added,
    then, please, feel free to EMAIL me:

        @{fg shine}Stefan Zakarias <stef@amitar.com.au>@{fg text}
@endnode

@node "Bugs" "Bugs"

                                   @{fg shine}BUGS@{fg text}

    Yep, there's got to be some hiding in there for sure...
    Tell ME if you find them!

    1.  MUI causes a lot of 'Mungwall' hits.  It's not my fault!

        This happens on almost ALL MUI based programs I've tested.  If the
        program tends to crash erratically, then increasing the stack may
        help!

    2.  To properly save the last used dimension and position of the ASL
        File Requester, you might have to open a File Requester, with the
        new dimension and position, TWICE in the program!  This is a bug in
        the "asl.library".
@endnode

