@node "TX_Status" "Status Bar"

                                  Status

    This tells you what processing state PGP5GUI is currently in.
    The possible messages are:

               Initializing - PGP5GUI start up.
                 Processing - Executing a PGP5 program.
           Getting key list - Updating key list.
        Generating key list - Generating list for PGP5GUI.
     Waiting for key choice - Waiting for your key selection.
    Waiting for file choice - Waiting for your file selection.
                     Ready! - Ready to perform a function.
@endnode

@node "Encrypt_Group" "Encrypt Page"

                                  @{fg shine}Encrypt@{fg text}

PURPOSE - File encryption.

DESCRIPTION

    This page is where file Encrypting operations are performed.

    On this page you will find:

    -   3 cycle gadgets for selecting the options you wish to use for
        encrypting an input file.

        These are (from the top):

                           @{"   Encryption Mode   " link "ENCRYPT_MODE" 0}

                           @{"   Use ASCII Armor   " link "ASCII_ARMOR" 0}

                           @{"  Text Mode ON/OFF   " link "TEXT_MODE" 0}

                           @{" Encrypt A File/Clip " link "Encrypt_CLIP" 0}

    -   A @{" File To Encrypt " link "FILE_ENCRYPT" 0} text string and @{" pop-File " link "Pop_ASLFile" 0} gadget used for
        selecting the file you wish to encrypt.

    -   An @{" Encrypt The File! " link "ENCRYPT_FILE" 0} button to begin the encryption process.
@endnode

@node "ENCRYPT_MODE" "Encryption Modes"

                               @{fg shine}Encrypt Mode@{fg text}

PURPOSE - Select method of Encryption.

DESCRIPTION
                            @{b}@{fg shine}Public Key Encrypt@{ub}@{fg text}

    This is the default method for encrypting a file.  This mode encrypts
    the file using the recipient's key you specify after you press
    @{" Encrypt The File! " link "ENCRYPT_FILE" 0}


                        @{b}@{fg shine}Public Key Encrypt And Sign@{ub}@{fg text}

    This mode encrypts the file using the recipient's key you specify after
    you press @{" Encrypt The File! " link "ENCRYPT_FILE" 0}  It also signs the file as well, using the
    default signing key specified in the @{" MyName= " link "PGP:PGP5.guide/PGP-CFG" 83} line of @{" pgp.cfg " link "PGP:PGP5.guide/PGP-CFG" 0}, or
    the first secret key found on your secret keyring.


                        @{b}@{fg shine}Conventional Encrypt (IDEA)@{ub}@{fg text}

    Conventional encryption mode.  This uses a symmetric cipher called
    "IDEA" to encrypt your message.  No public-key related information is
    used in this method.  This method depends on a mutual pass-phrase to be
    shared between the author and the recipient(s).
@endnode

@node "Encrypt_CLIP" "Encrypt File or Clip"

                            @{fg shine}Encrypt A File/Clip@{fg text}

PURPOSE - Selects encrypt a file or encrypt a clip in clipboard.

DESCRIPTION
                              @{b}@{fg shine}Encrypt A File@{ub}@{fg text}

    In this mode, the file with the name shown in the @{" File To Encrypt " link "FILE_ENCRYPT" 0}
    gadget is encrypted.


                              @{b}@{fg shine}Encrypt A Clip@{ub}@{fg text}

    If there is a clip in the system clipboard, then the clip is encrypted.
    To be compatible with the clipboard, the encryption options are set to:

                             @{" Use ASCII Armor " link "ASCII_ARMOR" 0}

                             @{"  Text Mode ON   " link "TEXT_MODE" 0}

    The encrypted clip is returned back to the clipboard, ready for pasting
    using a suitable text editor or program.

    Some text editors/programs use more than one clipboard unit number.
    The default 'clip' unit number used in PGP5GUI is unit 0.
@endnode

@node "FILE_ENCRYPT" "File To Encrypt"

                              @{fg shine}File To Encrypt@{fg text}

PURPOSE - Name of the file to encrypt.

DESCRIPTION

    This is where you enter the name of the file you wish to encrypt.

    To make it easier to select a file, there is a @{" pop-file " link "Pop_ASLFile" 0} gadget next to
    the file name entry box.

    You can also drag and drop a Workbench icon onto the @{" pop-file " link "Pop_ASLFile" 0} gadget,
    or the text entry gadget, to select a file.
@endnode

@node "ENCRYPT_FILE" "Encrypt The File"

                             @{fg shine}Encrypt The File!@{fg text}

PURPOSE - Begin the encryption process.

DESCRIPTION

    This starts the encryption process on the file, or clip, using the 
    settings you have specified.
@endnode

@node "Decrypt_Group" "Decrypt Page"

                                  @{fg shine}Decrypt@{fg text}

PURPOSE - Decrypt or verify a file/clip.

DESCRIPTION

    This is the page where Decrypting or Verifying an input file/clip is done.

    On it you will find:

    -   An @{" Output To... " link "DECRYPT_OUT" 0} cycle gadget for selecting the option you wish to
        use when decrypting an input file or for selecting a clip to decrypt
        or verify.

    -   A @{" File To Decrypt " link "FILE_DECRYPT" 0} text string and @{" pop-file " link "Pop_ASLFile" 0} gadget used for
        selecting the file you wish to decrypt.

    -   A @{" Decrypt The File! " link "DECRYPT_FILE" 0} button to begin the decryption process.
@endnode

@node "DECRYPT_OUT" "Decrypted File Output"

                             @{fg shine}File Output Mode@{fg text}

PURPOSE - Select output method used for decryption.

DESCRIPTION
                            @{b}@{fg shine}Output To File Only@{ub}@{fg text}

    This mode decrypts to a file using the name of the input file minus any
    filename extension after the last period - "." - in the filename.  PGP5
    normally encrypts a file using either a ".asc" or ".pgp" extension
    after the input filename so that when the recipient decrypts the file,
    they don't have to worry about what to name the file as.


                         @{b}@{fg shine}Output To Internal Pager@{ub}@{fg text}

    This mode displays the decrypted file using the internal pager of PGP5.
    If the file is binary, it will not be displayed!


                              @{b}@{fg shine}Output to Clip@{ub}@{fg text}

    An encrypted clip in the clipboard is decrypted.  The decrypted clip is
    returned back to the clipboard, ready for pasting using a suitable text
    editor or program.

    Some text editors, or programs, use more than one clipboard unit number.
    The default 'clip' unit number used in PGP5GUI is unit 0.
@endnode

@node "FILE_DECRYPT" "File To Decrypt or Verify"

                         @{fg shine}File To Decrypt Or Verify@{fg text}

PURPOSE - Name of the file to decrypt or verify.

DESCRIPTION

    This is where you enter the name of the file you wish to decrypt or
    verify.

    To make it easier to select a file, there is a @{" pop-file " link "Pop_ASLFile" 0} gadget next
    to the file name entry box.

    You can also drag and drop a Workbench icon onto the @{" pop-file " link "Pop_ASLFile" 0} gadget,
    or the text entry gadget, to select a file.
@endnode

@node "DECRYPT_FILE" "Decrypt The File"

                         @{fg shine}Decrypt/Verify The File!@{fg text}

PURPOSE - Begin the decryption/verifying process.

DESCRIPTION

    This starts the decryption/verifying process on the file/clip.

    The decrypting process will send the resulting output to either PGP5's
    internal pager, a file, or the clipboard.

    If a 'combined-signature' text file is to have it's signature verified,
    the signature is stripped and the stripped file, minus the file's '.asc'
    extension, is returned.

    If a 'combined-signature' text clip is to have it's signature verified,
    the signature is stripped and the stripped clip is returned.
@endnode

@node "Sign_Group" "Signing Page"

                                   @{fg shine}Sign@{fg text}

PURPOSE - File signing.

DESCRIPTION

    This page is where you can Sign an input file.

    Here you will find:

    -   3 cycle gadgets for selecting the options you wish to use for
        signing an input file.

        These are (from the top):

                        @{" Detached signature ON/OFF " link "SIGN_DETACH" 0}

                        @{"      Use ASCII Armor      " link "ASCII_ARMOR" 0}

                        @{"     Text Mode ON/OFF      " link "TEXT_MODE" 0}

                        @{"     Sign A File/Clip      " link "Sign_CLIP" 0}

    -   A @{" File To Sign " link "FILE_SIGN" 0} text string and @{" pop-file " link "Pop_ASLFile" 0} gadget used for selecting
        the input file you wish to sign.

    -   A @{" Sign The File! " link "SIGN_FILE" 0} button to begin the signing function.
@endnode

@node "SIGN_DETACH" "Detached Signature"

                          @{fg shine}Signature Output Method@{fg text}

PURPOSE - Select the method of signing a file.

DESCRIPTION
                           @{b}@{fg shine}Detached Signature ON@{ub}@{fg text}

    Creates a detached signature file using the input file's name with a
    ".sig" extension attached.  This mode is useful for signing binary
    files like, for example, executable files.


                          @{b}@{fg shine}Detached Signature OFF@{ub}@{fg text}

    Combines the signature with the input file.  In other words, the
    signature becomes part of the file.  This mode is mainly used for
    signing documents like, for example, Email.  This mode should NOT be
    used on binary files.
@endnode

@node "Sign_CLIP" "Sign Clip In Clipboard"

                             @{fg shine}Sign A File/Clip@{fg text}

PURPOSE - Selects sign a file or sign a clip in clipboard.

DESCRIPTION
                                @{b}@{fg shine}Sign A File@{ub}@{fg text}

    In this mode, the file with the name shown in the @{" File To Sign " link "FILE_SIGN" 0}
    gadget is PGP signed.


                                @{b}@{fg shine}Sign A Clip@{ub}@{fg text}

    If there is a clip in the system clipboard, then the clip is PGP signed.
    To be compatible with the clipboard, the signing options are locked at:

                         @{" Detached Signature OFF " link "SIGN_DETACH" 0}

                         @{"    Use ASCII Armor     " link "ASCII_ARMOR" 0}

                         @{"      Text Mode ON      " link "TEXT_MODE" 0}

    The signed clip is returned back to the clipboard, ready for pasting
    using a suitable text editor or program.  The signature is included in
    the clip.

    Some text editors/programs use more than one clipboard unit number.
    The default 'clip' unit number used in PGP5GUI is unit 0.
@endnode

@node "FILE_SIGN" "File To Sign"

                               @{fg shine}File To Sign@{fg text}

PURPOSE - Name of the file to sign.

DESCRIPTION

    This is where you enter the name of the file you wish to sign.

    To make it easier to select a file, there is a @{" pop-file " link "Pop_ASLFile" 0} gadget next
    to the file name entry box.

    You can also drag and drop a Workbench icon onto the @{" pop-file " link "Pop_ASLFile" 0} gadget,
    or the text entry gadget, to select a file.
@endnode

@node "SIGN_FILE" "Sign The File"

                               @{fg shine}Sign The File!@{fg text}

PURPOSE - Begin the file signing process.

DESCRIPTION

    This starts the signing process on the file, or clip, using the 
    settings you have specified.
@endnode

@node "ASCII_ARMOR" "ASCII Armoring Mode"

                              @{fg shine}ASCII Armoring@{fg text}

PURPOSE - Toggle "ASCII Armoring" ON or OFF.

DESCRIPTION

    With @{b}Use ASCII Armoring@{ub}, PGP5 creates a "text-only" version of the file
    being processed.  This makes the file safe for electronic mailing
    because most Email programs and servers are expecting text only when
    dealing with mail.  The downside of this is that the resulting file is
    about 30% larger than with @{b}No ASCII Armor@{ub}.

    This mode is also useful to create a message suitable for paper mailing
    or hard-copying.  The message can be printed to paper and later
    retrieved using a hand or page scanner with character recognition
    software.

    With @{b}No ASCII Armor@{ub}, PGP5 creates a binary output file.
@endnode

@node "TEXT_MODE" "Text Compatibility Mode"

                                 @{fg shine}Text Mode@{fg text}

PURPOSE - Toggles "Text Mode" ON or OFF.

DESCRIPTION

    This deals with the carriage-return/line-feed sequence differences
    between the major operating systems.

    With @{b}Text Mode ON@{ub}, PGP5 converts your input message to a platform
    independent form.  It's primary use is for when you expect or don't
    know that the recipient of the file may have a different operating
    system to the one you are using.  E.G:  AMIGA -> MAC/IBM.

    With @{b}Text Mode OFF@{ub}, PGP5 leaves the message untouched.
@endnode

@node "Pop_ASLFile" "Pop-File Requester"

                            @{fg shine}Pop-File Requester@{fg text}

PURPOSE - Pops up a standard ASL File Requester.

DESCRIPTION

    Clicking the left mouse button on this gadget will pop up a standard
    ASL file requester from which you can select the file you want to
    perform a specific function on.
@endnode

@node "Keys_Group" "Key Management Pages"

                         @{fg shine}Key Management Functions@{fg text}

PURPOSE - Pages with functions for managing your PGP keys.

DESCRIPTION

    On this page you will find 3 more pages with functions to use for
    managing your PGP keys.

    The pages are:

           @{"    Add - Add a key, or keys to your PGP keyring    " link "Keys_ADD" 0}

           @{" Edit - Edit details about PGP keys on your keyring " link "Keys_EDIT" 0}

           @{"  Misc - Miscellaneous functions for your keyring   " link "Keys_MISC" 0}
@endnode

@node "Keys_ADD" "Keys - Add Page"

                                @{fg shine}Keys - Add@{fg text}

PURPOSE - Add key(s) from an input file.

DESCRIPTION

    Provides you with 3 gadgets used for adding a key to your keyring.

    The first is a @{" Add Key(s) From A Clip/File " link "KeysAdd_CLIP" 0} selection gadget.
    This is where you select where you want to add keys from.

    The second is a @{" file name " link "ADD_KEYFILE" 0} input gadget where you can enter the name
    of the "keyfile" that contains a PGP key or keys.

    The last gadget is a button called @{" Add Key(s) In File To Keyring " link "ADD_KEYS" 0}.
    You press this button to begin the operation after you have selected a
    file.
@endnode

@node "KeysAdd_CLIP" "Add Keys From File Or Clip"

                        @{fg shine}Add Key(s) From A File/Clip@{fg text}

PURPOSE - Add keys from a file or from a clip in the clipboard.

DESCRIPTION
                          @{b}@{fg shine}Add Key(s) From A File@{ub}@{fg text}

    In this mode, the file shown in the @{" Add Key(s) From Input File " link "ADD_KEYFILE" 0} gadget
    is searched and any PGP keys found are added to your keyring.


                          @{b}@{fg shine}Add Key(s) From A Clip@{ub}@{fg text}

    If there is a clip in the system clipboard, then the clip is used for
    adding keys.  The clip is returned back to the clipboard unmodified,
    ready for re-using by a suitable text editor or program.

    Some text editors, or programs, use more than one clipboard unit number.
    The default 'clip' unit number used in PGP5GUI is unit 0.
@endnode

@node "ADD_KEYFILE" "Add Key(s) From Input File"

                      @{fg shine}File To Read A Key Or Keys From@{fg text}

PURPOSE - Name of the file to get a key or keys from.

DESCRIPTION

    This is where you enter the name of the file that contains a key or
    keys that you want added to your keyring.

    To make it easier to select a file, there is a @{" pop-file " link "Pop_ASLFile" 0} gadget next 
    to the file name entry box.

    You can also drag and drop a Workbench icon onto the @{" pop-file " link "Pop_ASLFile" 0} gadget,
    or the text entry gadget, to select a file.
@endnode

@node "ADD_KEYS" "Add Key(s) In File To Keyring"

                      @{fg shine}Add Key(s) In File To Keyring!@{fg text}

PURPOSE - Begins the process to add key(s) from a file or clip.

DESCRIPTION

    This begins the process to read an input file/clip you have specified.
    If any keys were found in the file, they will be added to your keyring.
@endnode

@node "Keys_EDIT" "Keys - Edit Page"

                                @{fg shine}Keys - Edit@{fg text}

PURPOSE - Key management functions.

DESCRIPTION

    On this page you will find 6 functions commonly used with managing your
    PGP keys:

            @{"  Check Key(s) - Check all details about keys(s)  " link "ED_KEYCHECK" 0}

            @{"   (En/Dis)able Key - Toggle the usage of a key   " link "ED_KEYDISABLE" 0}

            @{" Remove Signature - Remove a signature from a key " link "ED_REMOVESIG" 0}

            @{"      Sign A Key - Sign a key with YOUR key       " link "ED_KEYSIGN" 0}

            @{" Remove A Key - Remove a key from your keyring(s) " link "ED_KEYREMOVE" 0}

            @{"    Edit A Key - Edit the details about a key     " link "ED_KEYEDIT" 0}
@endnode

@node "ED_KEYCHECK" "Check Key(s)"

                               @{fg shine}Check Key(s)@{fg text}

PURPOSE - Check details of a key or keys.

DESCRIPTION

    *** A very slow operation ***

    This button allows you to check the details of keys on your public
    keyring.  When you click this button, a 'keylister' will be presented
    to you.

    If you select a key, PGPK will check/display only the details for that
    particular key.

    If no keys are selected, then ALL keys will be checked and displayed.

    When you click [Ok] in the keylister, the operation is begun.
@endnode

@node "ED_KEYDISABLE" "(En/Dis)able Key"

                             @{fg shine}(En/Dis)able Key@{fg text}


PURPOSE - Toggle the ability of PGP5 to use a key.

DESCRIPTION

    This function toggles enabling/disabling of a selected key on your
    keyring.  When you click this button, a 'keylister' will be presented
    to you.

    Selecting a key and clicking [Ok] in the keylister will begin the
    operation.
@endnode

@node "ED_REMOVESIG" "Remove Signature"

                             @{fg shine}Remove Signature@{fg text}

PURPOSE - Remove a signature from a key.

DESCRIPTION

    Removes a signature from a key.  When you click this button, a
    'keylister' will be presented to you.

    Selecting a key and clicking [Ok] in the keylister will begin the
    operation.
@endnode

@node "ED_KEYSIGN" "Sign A Key"

                                @{fg shine}Sign A Key@{fg text}

PURPOSE - Sign a key with your key.

DESCRIPTION

    Signs a selected key with your DEFAULT signing key.  The default
    signing key is the key you have specified in the @{" MyName= " link "PGP:PGP5.guide/PGP-CFG" 83} line of
    @{" pgp.cfg " link "PGP:PGP5.guide/PGP-CFG" 0}.  If no key is specified as the default, then PGPK will use
    the first key found on your keyring.

    When you click this button, a 'keylister' will be presented to you.

    Selecting a key and clicking [Ok] in the keylister will begin the
    operation.
@endnode

@node "ED_KEYREMOVE" "Remove A Key"

                               @{fg shine}Remove A Key@{fg text}

PURPOSE - Remove a key from your keyring(s).

DESCRIPTION

    Removes the key from your public keyring, and your secret keyring as
    well, if it is there.  When you click this button, a 'keylister' will
    be presented to you.

    Selecting a key and clicking [Ok] in the keylister will begin the
    operation.
@endnode

@node "ED_KEYEDIT" "Edit A Key"

                                @{fg shine}Edit A Key@{fg text}

PURPOSE - Edit details of a PGP key.

DESCRIPTION

    Edits the selected key.  If this is YOUR key, it allows you to edit
    your userid and passphrase.  If the key belongs to someone else, it
    allows you to edit the trust you have in that person as an introducer
    of new keys.

    When you click this button, a 'keylister' will be presented to you.

    Selecting a key and clicking [Ok] in the keylister will begin the
    operation.
@endnode

@node "Keys_MISC" "Keys - Miscellaneous Page"

                                @{fg shine}Keys - Misc@{fg text}

PURPOSE - Miscellaneous key functions.

DESCRIPTION

    On this page you will find 3 utility functions commonly used with
    managing your PGP keys:

                         @{"   Generate Key Pair    " link "MISC_KEYGEN" 0}

                         @{" Extract Key(s) To File " link "MISC_KEYEXTRACT" 0}

                         @{"      List Key(s)       " link "MISC_KEYLIST" 0}
@endnode

@node "MISC_KEYGEN" "Generate Key Pair"

                             @{fg shine}Generate Key Pair@{fg text}

PURPOSE - Generate a Secret/Public keypair.

DESCRIPTION

    This button begins the operation to generate a public/secret key pair
    for yourself.

    When you click this button, the operation is begun.
@endnode

@node "MISC_KEYEXTRACT" "Extract Key(s) To File"

                          @{fg shine}Extract Key(s) To File@{fg text}

PURPOSE - Extract selected keys to a file.

DESCRIPTION

    Extracts the selected key(s) in ASCII-armored form and saves it to a
    file specified by you via an ASL File Requester that will pop-up.

    When you click this button, a 'keylister' will be presented to you.

    Selecting a key, or keys, and clicking [Ok] in the keylister will begin
    the operation.
@endnode

@node "MISC_KEYLIST" "List Key(s)"

                                @{fg shine}List Key(s)@{fg text}

PURPOSE - Show general information about keys.

DESCRIPTION

    Shows a list of keys you have on your public keyring.  If any keys are
    selected, then PGPK will show more information about those keys.

    When you click this button, a 'keylister' will be presented to you.

    When you click [Ok] in the keylister, with NO keys selected, the
    operation is aborted.

    Selecting a key, or keys, and clicking [Ok] in the keylister will begin
    the operation.
@endnode

